      "span_text": "Glycosylation of S. aureus proteins was also recently studied. SRRPs (serine-rich repeat proteins) adhesions that mediate attachment to host and bacterial surfaces were found to be glycosylated [CITATION_3] . Moreover, glycosylation pathways have been investigated. Glycosyltransferases A and B have been identified as responsible for glycosylation of surface glycoprotein SraP (serine-rich adhesin for platelets) with a proven role in staphylococcal virulence [CITATION_4] ."
